I"ï<p>A while ago I was playing around with granny square variations and I made these pretty heart squares. I made 9 in total and they became the front of a cushion cover that I sold in <a href="https://www.etsy.com/uk/shop/JellybeanJunctionUK">my Etsy shop</a>.</p>

<p><img class="rounded img-fluid post-img mx-auto d-block" src="/assets/images/Snapseed_1.jpeg" /></p>

<p>The design is simple but effective and can be made using any yarn in any colours. I used aran weight cotton yarn to make these and decided on a two-tone heart with white surround.</p>

<p>I have written up the pattern for you to make your own‚Ä¶</p>

<p><strong>Heart Granny Square Pattern</strong></p>

<p>What you‚Äôll need:</p>

<ul>
  <li>3 colours of aran weight cotton yarn</li>
  <li>4mm crochet hook</li>
  <li>scissors</li>
  <li>darning needle</li>
</ul>

<p><img class="rounded img-fluid post-img mx-auto d-block" src="/assets/images/IMG_0625-768x768.jpeg" /></p>

<p>Abbreviations:</p>

<ul>
  <li>ch ‚Äì Chain</li>
  <li>st ‚Äì Stitch</li>
  <li>tr ‚Äì Treble Crochet (US Double Crochet)</li>
</ul>

<p>Pattern is written in UK terms. Beginning chain <strong>always</strong> counts as first stitch (unless otherwise stated). You are making a basic granny square but changing colours as you go to create the heart design.</p>

<p>‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äì</p>

<p>Using central colour (<strong><em>A</em></strong>) make a magic circle</p>

<p><img class="rounded img-fluid post-img mx-auto d-block" src="/assets/images/IMG_0613-2-768x768.jpeg" /></p>

<p>Round 1 ‚Äì (<strong><em>working into the magic circle</em></strong>) ch3, 2tr, *ch1, 3tr, repeat from * twice more, ch1 then ss to top of ch3, fasten off.</p>

<p><img class="rounded img-fluid post-img mx-auto d-block" src="/assets/images/IMG_0616-2-768x768.jpeg" /></p>

<p>Round 2 ‚Äì (<strong><em>Using colour B</em></strong>) join yarn in any ch1 space with a ss, ch3 (2tr, ch1, 3tr) into same space, (3tr, ch1, 3tr) into the 3 remaining ch1 spaces, ss to top of ch3.</p>

<p><img class="rounded img-fluid post-img mx-auto d-block" src="/assets/images/IMG_0617-2-768x768.jpeg" /></p>

<p>Round 3 ‚Äì ss along to corner space, ch3 (2tr, ch1, 3tr) into same space, 3tr in next space (<strong><em>change to colour C at the end of the 3rd tr</em></strong>), (3tr, ch1, 3tr) in corner space (<strong><em>change to colour B at the end of last tr</em></strong>), 3tr in next space (<strong><em>change to colour C at the end of the 3rd tr</em></strong>), (3tr, ch1, 3tr) in corner space (<strong><em>change back to colour B at the end of last tr</em></strong>), 3tr in next space, (3tr, ch1, 3tr) in next corner space (<strong><em>change to colour C at the end of last tr</em></strong>), 3tr in next space, ss to top of ch3.</p>

<p><img class="rounded img-fluid post-img mx-auto d-block" src="/assets/images/IMG_0619-1-768x768.jpeg" /></p>

<p><strong>TIP ‚Äì When crocheting round 4 try to crochet over as many of the ends from round 3 as possible, this will minimise the amount of ends to sew in.</strong></p>

<p>Round 4 ‚Äì ch3, *(3tr, ch1, 3tr) in corner space, 3tr in next 2 spaces, repeat from * twice, (3tr, ch1, 3tr) in last corner space, 3tr in next space, 2tr in last space, ss to top of ch3.</p>

<p><img class="rounded img-fluid post-img mx-auto d-block" src="/assets/images/Snapseed-1-768x768.jpeg" /></p>

<p>Round 5 ‚Äì ch3, 2tr in same space, *(3tr, ch1, 3tr) in corner space, 3tr in next 3 spaces, repeat from * twice, (3tr, ch1, 3tr) in last corner space, 3tr in next 2 spaces, ss to top of ch3, fasten off and sew in ends.</p>

<p>Block the square if necessary.</p>

